        <item>
            <guid isPermaLink="false">tag:noria.com,2010-06-10:publishing:magazines:rp:6168d4b2-a014-4760-901e-9e6f0093a1e9</guid>
            <link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/noria/reliableplant/tags/predictive_maintenance/~3/LtWSRF9Geig/Swirl-effect-broken-rotor-bars</link>
            <a10:author>
                <a10:name>PdMA Corporation</a10:name>
            </a10:author>
            <category>Industry News</category>
            <category>Articles</category>
            <title>PdMA tip: Swirl effect is useful tool for detecting broken rotor bars</title>
            <description>&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="width: 100%" width="100%"&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
				&lt;p&gt;
					A useful spectral tool for detecting broken rotor bars is the swirl effect, which occurs just below&amp;nbsp;the 5th harmonic of line frequency (300 Hz on a 60 Hz line frequency). Swirl peaks are a confirming tool for the pole-pass frequency sidebands around line frequency and occur at:&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;p&gt;
					&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &lt;em&gt;f&lt;sub&gt;swirl&lt;/sub&gt; = [1 - (2/5)ks]5f&lt;sub&gt;Line&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;p&gt;
					Where:&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;p&gt;
					f&lt;sub&gt;swirl &lt;/sub&gt;= location of the peaks&amp;nbsp;just below the 5&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; harmonic of line frequency&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;p&gt;
					k = harmonic index 1,2,3...&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;p&gt;
					s = Slip&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;p&gt;
					f&lt;sub&gt;Line &lt;/sub&gt;= line frequency&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;p&gt;
					For more information read &lt;em&gt;Using a Six Fault Zone Approach for Predictive Maintenance on Motors&lt;/em&gt; at &lt;a href="http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?llr=hviqffcab&amp;amp;et=1104246037014&amp;amp;s=4679&amp;amp;e=0011huPz59NNxWMB0sZqq9FSoQQx-KZClLsYsDBbxUzuyCj12mSLmoKIzipy-e1F45d_y_YioqHZ_FLJUiq2b1mkRAeTLf0kFu2f52PSSrLSNSMu-a4MSZyRknx_H1FcFnVM1R4rfzkkuWzoQASM2eRxkKwUOMBQd468nBjqubFEwQbby53l6R_vs7KoWKGkZ6YWmRKRp_k3eLpzdFtvoKUfAghpC6K2bFKaf9ZuLTfmiQ=" linktype="link" shape="rect" target="_blank" track="on"&gt;http://www.pdma.com/pdfs/Articles/Using_a_Six_Fault_Zone_Approach_for_Predictive_Maintenance_on_Motors.pdf&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;p&gt;
					&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/noria/reliableplant/tags/predictive_maintenance/~4/LtWSRF9Geig" height="1" width="1" alt=""/&gt;</description>
            <a10:updated>2011-01-18T08:57:28-06:00</a10:updated>
